Before you can manipulate elements, you need to select them. JavaScript provides several methods for selecting DOM elements, each with different use cases.

**Selection Methods:**

**1. getElementById()** - Fastest, selects by unique ID
```javascript
const title = document.getElementById('pageTitle');
console.log(title); // Returns the element or null
```
- Returns a single element
- Very fast (direct lookup)
- ID must be unique in the document
- Most commonly used method

**2. getElementsByClassName()** - Selects by class name
```javascript
const buttons = document.getElementsByClassName('btn');
console.log(buttons); // Returns HTMLCollection (array-like)
console.log(buttons[0]); // Access first element
```
- Returns multiple elements (HTMLCollection)
- Live collection (updates automatically)
- Can access by index

**3. getElementsByTagName()** - Selects by tag name
```javascript
const paragraphs = document.getElementsByTagName('p');
console.log(paragraphs.length); // Number of <p> elements
```
- Returns all elements with specified tag
- Useful for bulk operations
- Returns HTMLCollection

**4. querySelector()** - Modern, flexible CSS selector
```javascript
const firstButton = document.querySelector('.btn');
const header = document.querySelector('#header');
const activeLink = document.querySelector('a.active');
```
- Returns first matching element
- Supports any CSS selector
- More flexible but slightly slower
- Modern approach (IE9+)

**5. querySelectorAll()** - Selects all matching elements
```javascript
const allButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');
const allLinks = document.querySelectorAll('a');
const specificDivs = document.querySelectorAll('div.highlight');
```
- Returns NodeList (array-like)
- Static collection (doesn't auto-update)
- Supports any CSS selector
- Can use forEach() directly

**Selection Best Practices:**
```javascript
// Good - Store selections in variables
const mainTitle = document.getElementById('mainTitle');
const allButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');

// Good - Use specific selectors
const submitButton = document.querySelector('#submit-btn');
const activeItems = document.querySelectorAll('.item.active');

// Bad - Repeated selections (slow)
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  document.getElementById('title').style.color = 'red';
}

// Good - Select once, reuse
const title = document.getElementById('title');
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  title.style.color = 'red';
}
```

**Complete Example:**
```javascript
// Select different elements
const header = document.getElementById('header');
const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');
const firstParagraph = document.querySelector('p');
const allImages = document.getElementsByTagName('img');

// Check if element exists
if (header) {
  console.log('Header found!');
  header.style.color = 'blue';
}

// Loop through multiple elements
buttons.forEach(button => {
  button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log('Button clicked!');
  });
});
```

Once you've selected an element, you can modify its content, attributes, and styles. JavaScript provides multiple properties and methods for these operations.

**Content Modification:**

**textContent** - Text content only (safe)
```javascript
const paragraph = document.getElementById('message');
paragraph.textContent = 'Hello, World!';

// Get text content
console.log(paragraph.textContent);

// textContent ignores HTML tags
paragraph.textContent = '<strong>Bold</strong>'; // Shows as literal text
```
- Sets or gets text content
- Safe from XSS attacks
- Ignores HTML tags
- Faster than innerHTML

**innerHTML** - HTML content (use with caution)
```javascript
const container = document.getElementById('container');
container.innerHTML = '<p>New paragraph</p><button>Click me</button>';

// Get HTML content
console.log(container.innerHTML);
```
- Sets or gets HTML content
- Can insert HTML tags
- XSS vulnerability risk with user input
- Slower than textContent

**outerHTML** - Element plus its content
```javascript
const div = document.getElementById('myDiv');
div.outerHTML = '<section>New section</section>';
// Replaces the entire div element
```

**Form Values:**
```javascript
const input = document.getElementById('username');
const textarea = document.getElementById('message');
const select = document.getElementById('country');

// Get values
console.log(input.value);
console.log(textarea.value);
console.log(select.value);

// Set values
input.value = 'JohnDoe';
textarea.value = 'Hello there!';
select.value = 'USA';
```

**Attribute Modification:**
```javascript
const image = document.getElementById('myImage');
const link = document.getElementById('myLink');

// Get attributes
console.log(image.src);
console.log(link.href);
console.log(image.alt);

// Set attributes
image.src = 'new-image.jpg';
image.alt = 'A beautiful sunset';
link.href = 'https://example.com';
link.target = '_blank';

// Using setAttribute and getAttribute
image.setAttribute('src', 'new-image.jpg');
image.setAttribute('alt', 'Description');
console.log(image.getAttribute('src'));

// Remove attribute
image.removeAttribute('title');

// Check if attribute exists
if (image.hasAttribute('alt')) {
  console.log('Alt text exists');
}
```

**Class Manipulation:**
```javascript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');

// Add class
element.classList.add('highlight');
element.classList.add('active', 'featured'); // Multiple classes

// Remove class
element.classList.remove('highlight');
element.classList.remove('active', 'featured');

// Toggle class (add if absent, remove if present)
element.classList.toggle('active');

// Check if class exists
if (element.classList.contains('highlight')) {
  console.log('Element has highlight class');
}

// Replace class
element.classList.replace('old-class', 'new-class');

// Get all classes
console.log(element.classList); // DOMTokenList
console.log(element.className); // String of all classes
```

**Complete Example:**
```javascript
const card = document.getElementById('userCard');

// Modify content
card.querySelector('.name').textContent = 'John Doe';
card.querySelector('.email').textContent = 'john@example.com';

// Modify attributes
card.querySelector('img').src = 'john.jpg';
card.querySelector('img').alt = 'Profile picture of John Doe';

// Modify classes
card.classList.add('active');
card.classList.remove('hidden');

// Modify styles
card.style.backgroundColor = '#f0f0f0';
card.style.padding = '20px';
card.style.borderRadius = '10px';
```

JavaScript can dynamically change CSS styles, allowing you to create interactive and responsive user interfaces. There are multiple ways to apply styles programmatically.

**Inline Styles (style property):**
```javascript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');

// Set individual styles
element.style.color = 'red';
element.style.backgroundColor = 'blue';
element.style.fontSize = '20px';
element.style.padding = '10px';
element.style.borderRadius = '5px';

// CSS properties use camelCase in JavaScript
// background-color → backgroundColor
// font-size → fontSize
// border-radius → borderRadius
```
- Directly modifies element's style attribute
- Highest specificity (hard to override)
- Not recommended for large style changes
- Good for dynamic, one-off changes

**Getting Computed Styles:**
```javascript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');

// Get computed styles (all applied styles)
const computedStyle = window.getComputedStyle(element);
console.log(computedStyle.color);
console.log(computedStyle.fontSize);
console.log(computedStyle.backgroundColor);
```
- Returns all styles actually applied to element
- Includes inherited and default styles
- Read-only (cannot modify)
- Useful for debugging and calculations

**Class-Based Styling (Recommended):**
```javascript
const element = document.getElementById('myElement');

// Add pre-defined class
element.classList.add('highlight');
element.classList.add('error');
element.classList.remove('normal');

// Toggle class based on condition
if (isValid) {
  element.classList.add('success');
  element.classList.remove('error');
}
```
- Best practice for most cases
- Separates concerns (CSS in stylesheets)
- Easier to maintain
- Supports hover, active, media queries

**CSS Variables (Custom Properties):**
```javascript
// Set CSS variable
document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--primary-color', '#3498db');
document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--font-size', '16px');

// Get CSS variable
const primaryColor = getComputedStyle(document.documentElement)
  .getPropertyValue('--primary-color');
```
- Modern approach for theming
- Can be updated dynamically
- Affects all elements using the variable
- Great for dark mode, color themes

**Complete Example:**
```javascript
const button = document.getElementById('actionButton');
const card = document.getElementById('infoCard');

// Inline styles for dynamic values
button.style.transform = 'scale(1.1)';
button.style.opacity = '0.8';

// Class-based for structural changes
card.classList.add('highlight');
card.classList.remove('hidden');

// CSS variables for theming
document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--accent-color', '#e74c3c');

// Get computed values for calculations
const cardWidth = parseInt(window.getComputedStyle(card).width);
console.log(`Card width: ${cardWidth}px`);
```

Events are actions that occur in the browser, such as clicks, key presses, and form submissions. JavaScript can listen for these events and respond with appropriate actions.

**Common Event Types:**

**Mouse Events:**
- `click` - Mouse button pressed and released
- `dblclick` - Double click
- `mousedown` - Mouse button pressed
- `mouseup` - Mouse button released
- `mouseover` - Mouse enters element
- `mouseout` - Mouse leaves element
- `mousemove` - Mouse moves over element

**Keyboard Events:**
- `keydown` - Key pressed
- `keyup` - Key released
- `keypress` - Key pressed and released (deprecated)

**Form Events:**
- `submit` - Form submitted
- `input` - Input value changed
- `change` - Input value changed and focus lost
- `focus` - Element gains focus
- `blur` - Element loses focus

**Document/Window Events:**
- `load` - Page fully loaded
- `DOMContentLoaded` - HTML parsed and loaded
- `resize` - Window resized
- `scroll` - Page scrolled

**addEventListener() Method:**
```javascript
const button = document.getElementById('myButton');

// Basic event listener
button.addEventListener('click', function() {
  console.log('Button clicked!');
});

// Arrow function (modern)
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Button clicked!');
});

// Named function (reusable)
function handleClick() {
  console.log('Button clicked!');
}
button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);

// Multiple event listeners
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('First handler');
});
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Second handler');
});
```

**Event Object:**
```javascript
button.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  console.log('Event type:', event.type);
  console.log('Target element:', event.target);
  console.log('Current target:', event.currentTarget);
  console.log('Mouse position:', event.clientX, event.clientY);
  console.log('Key pressed:', event.key);

  // Prevent default behavior
  event.preventDefault();

  // Stop event propagation
  event.stopPropagation();
});
```

**preventDefault() - Stop Default Behavior:**
```javascript
// Prevent form submission
const form = document.getElementById('myForm');
form.addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // Stop form from submitting
  // Handle form data with JavaScript
});

// Prevent link navigation
const link = document.getElementById('myLink');
link.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // Stop link from navigating
  // Handle click with JavaScript
});
```

**Event Delegation - Efficient Event Handling:**
```javascript
// Instead of adding listeners to each button
const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');
buttons.forEach(btn => {
  btn.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
});

// Use event delegation on parent
const container = document.getElementById('buttonContainer');
container.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  if (event.target.classList.contains('btn')) {
    console.log('Button clicked:', event.target.textContent);
    // Handle button click
  }
});
```
- Single listener for multiple elements
- Works for dynamically added elements
- Better performance
- Cleaner code

**Removing Event Listeners:**
```javascript
function handleClick() {
  console.log('Clicked!');
}

button.addEventListener('click', handleClick);

// Remove specific listener
button.removeEventListener('click', handleClick);

// Remove all listeners (not directly possible)
// Clone element to remove all listeners
const newButton = button.cloneNode(true);
button.parentNode.replaceChild(newButton, button);
```

**Complete Example:**
```javascript
const form = document.getElementById('contactForm');
const input = document.getElementById('emailInput');

// Form submission
form.addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
  event.preventDefault();

  const email = input.value;
  if (validateEmail(email)) {
    console.log('Valid email:', email);
    // Submit form data
  } else {
    console.log('Invalid email');
    input.classList.add('error');
  }
});

// Input validation
input.addEventListener('input', function(event) {
  const email = event.target.value;
  if (validateEmail(email)) {
    input.classList.remove('error');
    input.classList.add('valid');
  } else {
    input.classList.remove('valid');
    input.classList.add('error');
  }
});

function validateEmail(email) {
  return email.includes('@') && email.includes('.');
}
```

JavaScript can dynamically create, modify, and remove DOM elements, allowing you to build interactive interfaces that respond to user actions and data changes.

**Creating Elements:**
```javascript
// Create new element
const newDiv = document.createElement('div');
const newParagraph = document.createElement('p');
const newButton = document.createElement('button');

// Set content
newParagraph.textContent = 'This is a new paragraph';
newButton.textContent = 'Click me';

// Set attributes
newDiv.id = 'newDiv';
newDiv.className = 'container';
newButton.type = 'button';
newButton.setAttribute('data-id', '123');

// Set styles
newDiv.style.backgroundColor = '#f0f0f0';
newDiv.style.padding = '20px';
```

**Appending Elements:**
```javascript
const parent = document.getElementById('container');
const child = document.createElement('div');
child.textContent = 'Child element';

// Append as last child
parent.appendChild(child);

// Append multiple children
parent.appendChild(document.createElement('p'));
parent.appendChild(document.createElement('span'));
```

**Inserting Elements:**
```javascript
const parent = document.getElementById('container');
const newElement = document.createElement('div');
const referenceElement = document.getElementById('reference');

// Insert before reference element
parent.insertBefore(newElement, referenceElement);

// Insert after (using insertAdjacentElement)
referenceElement.insertAdjacentElement('afterend', newElement);

// Insert at specific positions
parent.insertAdjacentElement('beforebegin', newElement); // Before parent
parent.insertAdjacentElement('afterbegin', newElement);  // First child
parent.insertAdjacentElement('beforeend', newElement);   // Last child
parent.insertAdjacentElement('afterend', newElement);    // After parent
```

**Removing Elements:**
```javascript
const element = document.getElementById('removeMe');
const parent = document.getElementById('container');

// Remove element (modern, simple)
element.remove();

// Remove via parent (older method)
parent.removeChild(element);

// Remove all children
while (parent.firstChild) {
  parent.removeChild(parent.firstChild);
}

// Clear all children (modern)
parent.innerHTML = '';
```

**Replacing Elements:**
```javascript
const oldElement = document.getElementById('oldElement');
const newElement = document.createElement('div');
newElement.textContent = 'New content';

// Replace element
oldElement.parentNode.replaceChild(newElement, oldElement);
```

**Document Fragments - Performance Optimization:**
```javascript
const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
const container = document.getElementById('container');

// Add elements to fragment (not in DOM yet)
for (let i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
  const div = document.createElement('div');
  div.textContent = `Item ${i}`;
  fragment.appendChild(div);
}

// Add fragment to DOM (single reflow)
container.appendChild(fragment);
```
- Improves performance for multiple additions
- Single DOM reflow instead of many
- Elements not visible until appended
- Best practice for bulk updates

**Complete Example - Dynamic List:**
```javascript
const list = document.getElementById('itemList');
const addButton = document.getElementById('addButton');
const input = document.getElementById('itemInput');

addButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
  const text = input.value.trim();

  if (text) {
    // Create list item
    const li = document.createElement('li');
    li.textContent = text;
    li.className = 'item';

    // Create delete button
    const deleteBtn = document.createElement('button');
    deleteBtn.textContent = '×';
    deleteBtn.className = 'delete-btn';

    // Add delete functionality
    deleteBtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      li.remove();
    });

    // Append button to list item
    li.appendChild(deleteBtn);

    // Append list item to list
    list.appendChild(li);

    // Clear input
    input.value = '';
    input.focus();
  }
});
```
